##5. IAM — identity, access management, and security for data engineers

##•	Create an IAM role for Glue with S3 read access to raw/ and S3 write access to cleaned/.

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [

    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:GetObject",
        "s3:ListBucket"
      ],
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:s3:::healthcare-datalake",
        "arn:aws:s3:::healthcare-datalake/raw/*"
      ]
    },

    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:PutObject"
      ],
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:s3:::healthcare-datalake/cleaned/*"
      ]
    }
  ]
}

-- Glue needs to read the raw claims files. It transforms the data.
-- Glue writes cleaned Parquet files.
-- Glue does not need permission to delete source files.

##•	Create an IAM role for Redshift with S3 read access to cleaned/ only.

--IAM policy for Redshift

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [

    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:GetObject",
        "s3:ListBucket"
      ],
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:s3:::healthcare-datalake",
        "arn:aws:s3:::healthcare-datalake/cleaned/*"
      ]
    }

  ]
}

-- Redshift only loads cleaned data.
-- Raw files may contain: Bad records, incomplete files and sensitive information
-- Redshift should access only validated and transformed data.

##•	Explain in plain English why Redshift should not have s3:DeleteObject permission.

-- Redshift should not have s3:DeleteObject permission because its responsibility is to read and load data, not managing storage. 
-- Granting delete access will increase the security risk and violates the principle of least privilege. 
-- If compromised, Redshift could accidentally or maliciously remove critical healthcare data.

##•	Explain what 'assume role' means in the context of a Glue job reading from S3.

-- Assume role means an AWS service temporarily takes on the permissions defined in an IAM role. 
-- In a Glue job, Glue assumes a role that grants S3 access, receives temporary credentials from AWS 
-- It performs the required operations, and then the credentials automatically expire when no longer needed.



